export const modernCoreBranchArticles:Record<string,ArticleSection[]>={
  'german-idealism':[
    section('overview','The problem inherited from Kant',[
      'German Idealism names a sequence of late eighteenth- and early nineteenth-century projects that began from the problems opened by Kant’s critical philosophy. Kant argued that knowledge is neither a passive copy of independently finished objects nor a creation unconstrained by the world. Experience has intelligible form because sensibility and understanding contribute forms and concepts through which objects can be experienced. Yet his distinctions between appearances and things in themselves, receptivity and spontaneity, nature and freedom, left successors asking whether critical philosophy had drawn stable boundaries or merely restated the divisions it hoped to explain.',
      'Fichte, Schelling, and Hegel each tried to show how apparently opposed terms belong within a more unified account of rational activity. Their systems differ sharply. Fichte begins from the self-positing activity required for experience and agency. Schelling refuses to make nature a mere object for a subject and seeks an account in which nature and spirit are intelligible expressions of one productive reality. Hegel reconstructs forms of consciousness, social recognition, institutions, art, religion, and philosophy as historically developing shapes of freedom. German Idealism is therefore an argument among systems, not a single claim that reality is only in someone’s head.',
      'The central question is how finite knowers can be answerable to an objective world while also recognizing that objectivity is available only through conceptual, practical, and social capacities. This question joins epistemology to metaphysics and freedom. A theory of knowledge must explain why thought can grasp reality; a theory of reality must explain how rational agency arises within nature; an ethics must explain how freedom becomes actual rather than remaining an inner wish. The idealists pursue unity without erasing difference, and much of their difficulty comes from attempting to demonstrate rather than merely announce that unity.'
    ],['epistemology','metaphysics','deontology'],['kant','fichte','schelling','hegel'],['Critique of Pure Reason','Wissenschaftslehre','Phenomenology of Spirit']),
    section('development','From critical philosophy to post-Kantian systems',[
      'Kant’s Critique of Pure Reason appeared in 1781 and was substantially revised in 1787. It transformed debates between rationalism and empiricism by asking what makes experience and a priori knowledge possible. The later critiques connected cognition to moral freedom, aesthetic judgment, organism, and purposiveness. Kant is best presented as the decisive source and precursor of German Idealism, not simply as another system-builder of the same kind as Fichte, Schelling, and Hegel. He defended limits on speculative knowledge that his successors often judged unstable or insufficiently derived.',
      'In the 1790s Fichte recast critical philosophy around the activity of the I. His Wissenschaftslehre was repeatedly rewritten, so it should not be reduced to one slogan about the ego creating reality. The finite subject encounters resistance, obligation, other rational beings, and a world of action. Schelling first worked near Fichte, then developed philosophies of nature, identity, art, and freedom that challenged a one-sided priority of subjectivity. Nature had to be productive and intelligible in its own right, not dead material awaiting organization by mind.',
      'Hegel’s Phenomenology of Spirit of 1807 follows forms of consciousness through failures that reveal more adequate standards of knowledge and freedom. His later Science of Logic, Encyclopedia, and Philosophy of Right present a systematic architecture of logic, nature, spirit, and institutions. German Idealism did not simply end with Hegel. Schopenhauer, Kierkegaard, Marx, later neo-Kantians, phenomenologists, pragmatists, and critical theorists defined projects through selective inheritance and opposition. Its history is a branching reception rather than a straight ascent to a final system.'
    ],['rationalism','empiricism','continental-philosophy'],['kant','fichte','schelling','hegel','schopenhauer','kierkegaard','marx'],['Critique of Pure Reason','Science of Logic','Philosophy of Right']),
    section('concepts','Activity, idealism, dialectic, and freedom',[
      'Transcendental idealism concerns the conditions under which objects can be experienced and known. It is not the everyday thought that optimism makes things better, nor the simple metaphysical claim that only private ideas exist. Kant distinguishes empirical reality from claims about things considered apart from the conditions of possible experience. Post-Kantian thinkers ask whether a thing in itself can coherently function as an unknowable source or limit. Their stronger idealisms seek to understand objectivity within an account of reason that includes its own relation to what appears other than reason.',
      'Activity and self-consciousness are central because knowing is not mere reception. For Fichte, the I is an act rather than an inner object, and finite agency becomes determinate through limitation. Hegel likewise argues that self-consciousness depends on relations of recognition: a self becomes intelligible through practical relations with other selves, not through solitary inspection. Schelling presses the complementary question of how nature can generate organisms and consciousness. Across these projects, subjectivity is embodied, constrained, and world-involving even when the vocabulary can sound excessively mental.',
      'Dialectic names the movement by which a form of thought or life exposes tensions within its own standards and is reorganized into a more adequate form. Hegel did not generally employ the textbook formula “thesis, antithesis, synthesis” as a universal machine. Determinate negation preserves what a position achieved while identifying why it cannot stand as complete. Freedom likewise means more than arbitrary choice. It requires intelligible agency, recognition, and institutions in which persons can understand laws and practices as compatible with rational self-determination.'
    ],['metaphysics','epistemology','political-philosophy'],['fichte','schelling','hegel'],['Phenomenology of Spirit','Philosophy of Right']),
    section('figures-works','Four distinct projects and their major works',[
      'Kant’s Critique of Pure Reason asks how mathematics, natural science, and metaphysical questioning are possible while restricting claims that outrun experience. The Groundwork and Critique of Practical Reason locate moral obligation in autonomy, and the Critique of Judgment examines aesthetic judgment and purposiveness. These works supply problems and vocabulary for the movement, but Kant’s insistence on critical limits distinguishes him from successors seeking a self-grounding system. Reading him first helps prevent later systems from appearing as unmotivated metaphysical extravagance.',
      'Fichte’s Introductions to the Wissenschaftslehre offer a more accessible route than assuming there is a single definitive version of his system. They connect self-consciousness, practical striving, and the conditions of experience. Schelling’s writings change markedly: the Ideas for a Philosophy of Nature treats nature as dynamic productivity, the System of Transcendental Idealism gives art an exceptional role, and Philosophical Investigations into the Essence of Human Freedom explores evil, personality, and a ground not exhausted by transparent rational order.',
      'Hegel’s Phenomenology of Spirit dramatizes an education of consciousness through sense-certainty, self-consciousness, reason, social life, religion, and absolute knowing. The Science of Logic examines categories such as being, essence, concept, and actuality without treating logic as merely formal. The Philosophy of Right studies property, morality, family, civil society, and state. Its defense of institutions must be read alongside its account of modern freedom and its limitations, not converted either into a simple apology for authority or a manifesto for revolution.'
    ],['deontology','political-philosophy','continental-philosophy'],['kant','fichte','schelling','hegel'],['Critique of Pure Reason','Groundwork of the Metaphysics of Morals','Philosophical Investigations into Human Freedom','Phenomenology of Spirit']),
    section('debates','Disputes within the movement',[
      'One dispute concerns whether Kant’s thing in itself protects realism and intellectual humility or introduces an unintelligible cause beyond possible knowledge. Fichte tries to derive objectivity from the structure of finite self-activity, but critics worry that this makes nature dependent on subjectivity. Schelling answers that nature must be understood as productive in its own right. Hegel argues that an absolute boundary between thought and being cannot be asserted without already thinking both sides. The disagreement is not “world or no world,” but what makes independence and objectivity intelligible.',
      'A second dispute concerns system and freedom. If reality is a rational whole, can novelty, evil, contingency, and individual action be genuine? Schelling’s freedom essay insists that personality and evil cannot be explained as minor defects in an otherwise transparent order. Hegel describes freedom as achieved through social and historical forms, inviting the question whether his retrospective narratives make suffering look necessary or justified. Fichte emphasizes striving and obligation, but the endless character of striving raises its own questions about reconciliation.',
      'Political interpretations divide over the relation between rational institutions and critique. Hegel’s account of recognition and civil society has inspired emancipatory readings, while his state and philosophy of history contain exclusions and Eurocentric judgments. Kant’s cosmopolitan and republican writings coexist with claims shaped by racial hierarchies. A responsible presentation neither dismisses the tradition as authoritarian abstraction nor hides its exclusions behind the grandeur of system. Its resources for freedom must be tested against the people and histories its canonical accounts marginalized.'
    ],['political-philosophy','ethics','metaphysics'],['kant','fichte','schelling','hegel','marx'],['Philosophy of Right','Perpetual Peace']),
    section('neighbors','Neighbors, reactions, and transformations',[
      'German Idealism grows from early modern epistemology. Descartes, Spinoza, and Leibniz make reason, systematic explanation, and the relation of mind to world central; Locke and Hume sharpen questions about experience, causation, and the limits of inference. Kant transforms rather than merely compromises between rationalism and empiricism. Post-Kantian systems then connect this epistemological inheritance to aesthetics, theology, nature, politics, and history. The movement therefore sits at a crossroads linking metaphysics, epistemology, ethics, and philosophy of religion.',
      'Romanticism overlaps with the idealists through concerns about art, organism, fragmentation, and the limits of discursive reason, though it is not interchangeable with them. Marx transforms Hegelian themes of alienation, labor, and history through material and political critique. Kierkegaard attacks the danger that systematic mediation will dissolve the concrete existing individual. Schopenhauer retains Kantian distinctions while rejecting optimistic accounts of rational development. These reactions show that existentialism and political critique inherit German Idealism partly by refusing its ambitions.',
      'Phenomenology continues questions about subjectivity and world while changing method. Husserl’s transcendental project has Kantian ancestry; Heidegger reworks questions of finitude, history, and being; later continental philosophy repeatedly returns to Hegelian recognition and negativity. Analytic traditions were often narrated as a break from idealism, especially through Russell and Moore, but contemporary work has reopened exchanges around conceptual normativity, action, and social freedom. The borders are historical constructions, not walls separating unrelated philosophical languages.'
    ],['rationalism','empiricism','existentialism','phenomenology','continental-philosophy'],['descartes','spinoza','leibniz','hume','marx','kierkegaard','schopenhauer','husserl'],['Critique of Pure Reason','The World as Will and Representation']),
    section('misconceptions','Caricatures that obscure the arguments',[
      'Idealism does not mean cheerful aspiration, denial that tables and bodies exist, or the fantasy that an individual mind invents the universe. Different idealisms make different claims about the conditions of objectivity, the dependence of intelligibility on concepts, and the relation between subject and object. Fichte’s I is not simply his private personality; Schelling’s nature is not inert appearance; Hegel’s absolute is not a supernatural object standing outside history. Translating technical terms into familiar slogans without reconstructing their problem produces avoidable nonsense.',
      'Hegelian dialectic is not a three-step template into which any topic can be placed. Nor does “the rational is actual” mean that whatever happens is morally good. Hegel distinguishes actuality in a demanding sense from bare existence and evaluates institutions according to whether freedom is realized within them. Even so, his judgments are contestable and historically limited. Correcting the slogan should not become a way of immunizing Hegel from political criticism; it should make criticism address his actual standards and arguments.',
      'Finally, German Idealism is not one continuous system authored by four men. Kant remains a critical precursor whose limits motivate the movement. Fichte’s practical idealism, Schelling’s changing philosophies of nature and freedom, and Hegel’s historical systematic project cannot be substituted for one another. The tradition’s canonical roster also reflects institutions that excluded many voices. Teaching its internal sequence is valuable when presented as a contested conversation with later critics rather than an inevitable culmination of modern philosophy.'
    ],['analytic-philosophy','continental-philosophy'],['kant','fichte','schelling','hegel'],['Science of Logic']),
    section('modern-relevance','Why the idealist questions remain live',[
      'Contemporary debates about perception and conceptual content still ask whether experience can justify belief without already possessing intelligible form. Debates about artificial intelligence raise related questions: does manipulating representations amount to understanding, and what role do self-consciousness, embodiment, and social recognition play in minded agency? German Idealism does not supply ready-made answers, but it challenges models that treat intelligence as passive input processing or isolate a mind from its practical world.',
      'The idealists also matter for social freedom. A person may face no immediate interference yet lack institutions, recognition, education, or material conditions needed to act as an equal. Hegel’s distinction between abstract choice and socially actual freedom informs debates about family, markets, law, and democratic membership. Fichte’s accounts of agency and recognition and Kant’s autonomy remain sources for theories of responsibility. Their limitations help contemporary thinkers ask whose standing is recognized and whose dependence is rendered invisible.',
      'Environmental philosophy has renewed interest in Schelling’s refusal to understand nature as mere external material. His philosophy cannot simply be labeled ecological, but it offers conceptual resistance to a picture in which rational freedom confronts a meaningless mechanism. Historical memory likewise tests idealist narratives of development: can a society interpret progress without treating violence as a necessary stage? The tradition remains useful when its ambition to connect knowledge, nature, and freedom is joined to vigilance about totalizing stories.'
    ],['philosophy-of-mind','political-philosophy','philosophy-of-science'],['schelling','hegel','kant'],['Philosophy of Right']),
    section('reading-path','A route through a difficult tradition',[
      'Begin with a reliable overview of Kant’s distinction between appearances and things in themselves, then read the Prolegomena or selected portions of the Critique of Pure Reason on space, categories, and experience. Add the Groundwork to see why freedom is practical as well as epistemic. Move next to Fichte’s accessible Introductions to the Wissenschaftslehre, asking how self-conscious activity can be limited by a world and other agents. Read Schelling’s freedom essay after a short guide to his earlier nature and identity philosophies.',
      'Approach Hegel through the Preface and Introduction to the Phenomenology of Spirit, but do not assume the Preface is easy because it comes first. A guided selection on sense-certainty, recognition, and spirit is more useful than rushing through every chapter. Follow with selections from the Philosophy of Right on abstract right, civil society, and the state. Keep a glossary, but record each term as an answer to a problem rather than as a detached definition.',
      'Advanced study should compare the idealists instead of reading them as steps toward Hegel. Revisit Kant’s critical limits, compare Fichte’s accounts across versions, follow changes in Schelling, and read Hegel’s Logic alongside commentary. Then test the tradition through Marx, Kierkegaard, Schopenhauer, phenomenology, and contemporary work on recognition. The best checkpoint is whether one can explain why each thinker found the previous position unstable without claiming that the successor simply solved it.'
    ],['epistemology','metaphysics','existentialism'],['kant','fichte','schelling','hegel','marx','kierkegaard'],['Prolegomena','Introductions to the Wissenschaftslehre','Phenomenology of Spirit'])
  ],
  existentialism:[
    section('overview','Existing without a complete script',[
      'Existentialism gathers philosophical and literary work centered on the lived task of becoming a person under conditions that do not provide a complete script. Human beings find themselves embodied, mortal, historically situated, and answerable for choices whose consequences cannot be known in advance. Questions about anxiety, despair, authenticity, absurdity, responsibility, and meaning arise from this condition. Existential thinkers differ about religion, metaphysics, politics, and ethics, but they resist accounts that make an individual life fully intelligible from an impersonal system or fixed essence.',
      'The label must be handled historically. Kierkegaard and Nietzsche wrote before existentialism existed as a named twentieth-century movement and are better treated as precursors or decisive influences. Heidegger’s analysis of existence deeply shaped the movement, but he rejected Sartre’s humanist formulation. Sartre and Beauvoir worked within the French existentialist moment while developing distinct positions. Camus was closely associated with its questions and social circle but rejected the existentialist label; his philosophy of the absurd and revolt should not be silently absorbed into Sartre’s project.',
      'Existentialism’s central problem is not whether life feels gloomy. It is how a finite person can live responsibly when inherited values, social roles, religious assurances, or philosophical systems no longer settle what must be done. Some thinkers answer through religious commitment, others through value creation, freedom, ambiguity, solidarity, or revolt. None makes choice magically unconstrained. The question is how responsibility persists within facticity: the body, past, relationships, institutions, oppression, and historical circumstances that a person did not choose.'
    ],['ethics','phenomenology','philosophy-of-religion'],['kierkegaard','nietzsche','sartre','beauvoir','camus','heidegger'],['Fear and Trembling','Being and Nothingness','The Ethics of Ambiguity']),
    section('development','Precursors and the twentieth-century movement',[
      'Kierkegaard’s nineteenth-century pseudonymous writings challenge attempts to convert existence into a completed system. They examine anxiety, despair, ethical commitment, faith, and the difficulty of becoming a self. Nietzsche diagnoses how values are historically produced, announces the cultural consequences of the “death of God,” and asks what forms of life might overcome nihilism. Neither offered the doctrine later called existentialism. Their differences—Christian commitment in Kierkegaard, genealogical critique and value creation in Nietzsche—remain as important as their shared attention to individual transformation.',
      'Phenomenology supplied twentieth-century tools for describing existence. Heidegger’s Being and Time analyzes being-in-the-world, care, temporality, anxiety, death, and authenticity, shifting attention away from a detached spectator. Sartre’s Being and Nothingness recasts phenomenological themes through consciousness, negation, freedom, bad faith, and conflict with others. Beauvoir’s novels and philosophical works show freedom as embodied, reciprocal, and socially unequal. The Ethics of Ambiguity and The Second Sex make oppression and situated agency central rather than secondary applications of an abstract freedom.',
      'Camus analyzes the absurd as a confrontation between the human demand for intelligibility and a world that gives no guaranteed answer. The Myth of Sisyphus rejects both literal suicide and philosophical escapes from the problem; The Rebel investigates revolt, solidarity, and the danger that rebellion becomes murderous justification. After the Second World War, existential themes entered anticolonial, feminist, religious, psychiatric, and literary work. Fanon, for example, transforms phenomenological and existential resources through the lived violence of racialization and colonialism, without being reducible to a standard existentialist school member.'
    ],['phenomenology','feminist-philosophy','continental-philosophy'],['kierkegaard','nietzsche','heidegger','sartre','beauvoir','camus','fanon'],['Being and Time','The Second Sex','The Rebel']),
    section('concepts','Freedom, facticity, authenticity, and the absurd',[
      'Freedom in existentialism is not unlimited control. Sartre argues that consciousness takes a stance toward situations and cannot become a fixed thing with a predetermined meaning. Yet a person chooses only from a body, past, language, social position, and field of possibilities. Facticity names these given conditions. Beauvoir’s situated freedom makes especially clear that oppression can systematically restrict possibilities and force some people to spend their agency resisting conditions others treat as natural. Responsibility must therefore be paired with analysis of power.',
      'Bad faith is the attempt to flee the tension between freedom and facticity. A person may pretend to be nothing but a role, as though occupation or reputation mechanically determines action, or may imagine being pure freedom untouched by commitments and consequences. Authenticity is not a license to express whatever impulse feels most private. It concerns lucidly owning one’s situated choices without converting the self into either a fixed object or an unconditioned will. Kierkegaard’s account of selfhood and Heidegger’s authenticity differ substantially from Sartre’s vocabulary.',
      'Anxiety reveals possibility and the absence of guarantees; despair can name a distorted relation of the self to itself; absurdity names a conflict between the demand for meaning and an indifferent world. These terms are not interchangeable diagnoses. Kierkegaard relates anxiety and despair to freedom, selfhood, and faith. Heidegger distinguishes anxiety from fear directed at a particular object. Camus’s absurd is neither a property of the world alone nor proof that nothing matters. It is a relation that calls for lucid endurance and revolt.'
    ],['ethics','phenomenology','philosophy-of-mind'],['kierkegaard','heidegger','sartre','beauvoir','camus'],['The Concept of Anxiety','Being and Nothingness','The Myth of Sisyphus']),
    section('figures-works','Different voices, not one doctrine',[
      'Kierkegaard’s Either/Or stages competing forms of life; Fear and Trembling examines faith through the disturbing story of Abraham; The Concept of Anxiety and The Sickness Unto Death analyze freedom and selfhood. The pseudonyms are philosophical perspectives, not transparent statements of the author’s settled view. Nietzsche’s The Gay Science, Thus Spoke Zarathustra, and On the Genealogy of Morality combine aphorism, genealogy, provocation, and psychological diagnosis. His value creation is not a casual decision to call anything good.',
      'Heidegger’s Being and Time is an ontological inquiry using human existence to reopen the question of being, not a self-help manual about facing death. Its account of everyday conformity, care, and temporality profoundly influenced existentialism, while Heidegger’s involvement with Nazism creates an unavoidable question about the relation between his philosophy and politics. Sartre’s Being and Nothingness gives the most systematic account of consciousness and bad faith; Existentialism Is a Humanism offers an accessible but compressed public defense that should not substitute for the larger work.',
      'Beauvoir’s The Ethics of Ambiguity argues that freedom seeks a world in which others can also be free. The Second Sex analyzes how woman is socially constituted as Other while refusing biological or psychological destiny. Camus’s The Myth of Sisyphus and The Rebel move from absurdity to limits and solidarity. Presenting Beauvoir as merely applying Sartre or Camus as merely illustrating absurdism misses original arguments that revise the movement’s accounts of freedom, ethics, violence, and relation to others.'
    ],['philosophy-of-religion','feminist-philosophy','political-philosophy'],['kierkegaard','nietzsche','heidegger','sartre','beauvoir','camus'],['Either/Or','On the Genealogy of Morality','Being and Time','The Second Sex']),
    section('debates','Religion, ethics, politics, and other people',[
      'Existential approaches divide over religion. Kierkegaard sees faith as a passionate task that cannot be replaced by detached proof or social conformity. Nietzsche interprets Christian morality genealogically and asks what follows when its authority collapses. Sartre treats human freedom without a divine legislator, while religious existentialists develop different accounts of transcendence and commitment. It is misleading to define the movement as inherently atheist or inherently religious; the disagreement about God changes what anxiety, guilt, hope, and responsibility mean.',
      'A second debate asks whether existential freedom can support ethics. If values are not given as objective objects, why is one choice better than another? Sartre’s early formulations invite criticism that choice becomes arbitrary. Beauvoir answers through ambiguity, reciprocity, and the material conditions of others’ freedom. Camus grounds limits in solidarity born through revolt. These are contested arguments, but they show that existentialism does not end with “make your own meaning.” It asks how projects implicate other people and how freedom can betray itself through domination.',
      'Relations with others create another fault line. Sartre often emphasizes conflict, objectification, and the gaze. Beauvoir analyzes both conflict and possibilities of mutual recognition while showing how gendered institutions block reciprocity. Levinas later criticizes approaches that begin from the self’s freedom, arguing that responsibility to the other is more fundamental. Political disputes about Marxism, colonialism, violence, and collective action further test whether existential categories illuminate shared structures or overprivilege dramatic individual decision.'
    ],['philosophy-of-religion','ethics','feminist-philosophy','political-philosophy'],['kierkegaard','nietzsche','sartre','beauvoir','camus','levinas'],['The Ethics of Ambiguity','The Rebel']),
    section('neighbors','Phenomenology, religion, feminism, and critique',[
      'Existentialism’s closest methodological neighbor is phenomenology. Heidegger transforms Husserl’s study of intentional experience into an analysis of being-in-the-world. Sartre, Beauvoir, and Merleau-Ponty use phenomenological description to examine freedom, embodiment, perception, and social relations. Yet phenomenology is broader than existentialism, and not every phenomenologist is an existentialist. The relationship is an inheritance and transformation, not an identity between two labels.',
      'Philosophy of religion supplies both sources and opponents. Kierkegaard’s accounts of faith, inwardness, and despair cannot be understood if their Christian setting is removed. Nietzsche’s critique likewise addresses religious and moral formations rather than an abstract mood of unbelief. Ethics and political philosophy become unavoidable when existential freedom encounters promises, exploitation, war, race, gender, and institutions. Beauvoir and Fanon demonstrate why social situation is constitutive of experience rather than an optional context added afterward.',
      'Existentialism also overlaps with literature because narrative and drama can show ambiguity that a formal treatise flattens. Kierkegaard’s pseudonyms, Nietzsche’s styles, Sartre’s plays, Beauvoir’s novels, and Camus’s fiction are modes of philosophical inquiry as well as illustrations. Psychoanalysis, hermeneutics, and critical theory challenge its accounts of transparent choice by emphasizing unconscious life, inherited meanings, and structural power. These neighbors do not refute existentialism automatically; they make its idea of responsibility more demanding.'
    ],['phenomenology','philosophy-of-religion','feminist-philosophy','political-philosophy'],['husserl','heidegger','merleau-ponty','beauvoir','fanon'],['The Second Sex']),
    section('misconceptions','Beyond pessimism and motivational slogans',[
      'Existentialism is not the claim that life is pointless. It begins from the absence of an externally guaranteed script and asks what commitments remain possible. Kierkegaard finds meaning through a difficult religious relation; Nietzsche asks how values can be transformed; Sartre emphasizes projects and responsibility; Beauvoir argues for reciprocal freedom; Camus defends lucid revolt and solidarity. Their answers conflict, but none is captured by passive despair. Anxiety and absurdity are openings for analysis, not conclusions that action is futile.',
      'The tradition also does not teach that anyone can become anything by choosing hard enough. Bodies, histories, economic conditions, oppression, and consequences are real. Sartre’s language of radical freedom can sound voluntarist when isolated, but facticity is integral to his account, and Beauvoir makes unequal situations central. A person may remain responsible for a response without being responsible for having been oppressed, injured, or denied opportunities. Confusing these claims can turn existential responsibility into blame directed at victims.',
      'Finally, the roster requires label caution. Kierkegaard and Nietzsche are precursors rather than self-described existentialists. Heidegger resisted Sartre’s humanist interpretation. Camus explicitly rejected the existentialist label even though his problems belong in the conversation. Beauvoir is an independent philosopher, not a secondary commentator on Sartre. Using “existentialist” as a loose family resemblance can aid learning only when these historical differences remain visible.'
    ],['ethics','continental-philosophy'],['kierkegaard','nietzsche','heidegger','sartre','beauvoir','camus'],['Existentialism Is a Humanism']),
    section('modern-relevance','Situated agency in contemporary life',[
      'Existential questions recur when algorithms, institutions, or professional roles encourage people to describe decisions as automatic. Bad faith offers a vocabulary for the temptation to hide behind a role, a metric, or “what the system required,” while facticity prevents the opposite fantasy that an individual can simply opt out of every structure. The tradition asks where judgment remains possible, what responsibility attaches to participation, and how institutions can enlarge or constrict meaningful agency.',
      'Medicine and disability studies use existential and phenomenological resources to study how illness changes time, possibility, dependence, and identity. Climate anxiety similarly combines facts no individual controls with choices whose effects are collective and uncertain. Existentialism cannot turn planetary crisis into a private test of authenticity, but its accounts of anxiety, finitude, commitment, and solidarity can clarify why action remains meaningful without assurance of success.',
      'Beauvoir’s situated freedom and analyses of otherness remain influential in feminist and social philosophy. Fanon’s work shows how racial and colonial power shapes bodily experience and available identities. Camus’s concern with revolt and limits speaks to political movements tempted to justify any violence by a promised future. These uses are strongest when existential categories are joined to historical and institutional analysis, not offered as universal slogans detached from unequal conditions.'
    ],['feminist-philosophy','political-philosophy','phenomenology'],['beauvoir','fanon','camus'],['The Second Sex','The Rebel']),
    section('reading-path','How to enter the conversation',[
      'Begin with shorter texts that disclose differences rather than searching for one creed. Read Sartre’s Existentialism Is a Humanism as a public intervention, then question its compressed claims with Beauvoir’s Ethics of Ambiguity. Read Camus’s Myth of Sisyphus while remembering his rejection of the existentialist label. Add selected passages from Kierkegaard’s Fear and Trembling and Nietzsche’s Gay Science, using introductions that explain pseudonyms, aphorism, and nineteenth-century religious context.',
      'Next read phenomenological foundations selectively: portions of Heidegger’s Being and Time on being-in-the-world, anxiety, and death; Sartre on bad faith; Beauvoir’s introduction to The Second Sex; and Camus on revolt. Pair philosophical works with a novel or play, but do not treat fiction as an easy substitute. Ask in each work what is given, what can be chosen, how other people enter, and what would make a commitment responsible.',
      'Advanced reading should compare rather than homogenize. Study Kierkegaard’s pseudonymous authorship, Nietzsche’s genealogy, Heidegger’s ontology and politics, Sartre’s changing political commitments, Beauvoir’s phenomenology of oppression, and Camus’s dispute with revolutionary violence. Follow with Fanon and Levinas to test the priority given to freedom. A successful reading path ends not with a definition of existentialism, but with a map of disagreements about situated agency, meaning, and responsibility.'
    ],['phenomenology','ethics','political-philosophy'],['kierkegaard','nietzsche','heidegger','sartre','beauvoir','camus','fanon','levinas'],['Existentialism Is a Humanism','The Ethics of Ambiguity','The Myth of Sisyphus'])
  ],
  phenomenology:[
    section('overview','Describing how a world becomes present',[
      'Phenomenology is a family of methods and projects concerned with the structures through which things become meaningful in experience. It begins neither from a detached inventory of external objects nor from a sealed inner theater of private sensations. Consciousness is ordinarily directed toward something: a remembered friend, a threatening sound, a mathematical proof, a tool ready for use. Phenomenology investigates this directedness, the horizons that make an object intelligible, and the embodied and temporal conditions through which a world is given.',
      'Husserl founded phenomenology as a rigorous philosophical project, but later figures transformed its starting point. Heidegger shifted from an analysis centered on consciousness to being-in-the-world and the question of being. Sartre and Beauvoir used phenomenological description to study freedom, bad faith, otherness, and oppression. Merleau-Ponty made embodied perception central. Levinas inherited and criticized phenomenology by arguing that ethical responsibility to the other exceeds attempts to contain alterity within the knower’s horizons. Later phenomenologies extend these methods into medicine, technology, race, gender, disability, and environmental experience.',
      'The central problem is how experience can disclose an objective, shared world while always occurring from a situated perspective. Phenomenology refuses the assumption that perspective makes experience merely subjective or unreliable. A perspective can reveal stable structures, practical meanings, and the presence of others, even though no view is complete. The project is descriptive but not a transcript of whatever someone happens to feel. It requires disciplined distinctions among kinds of experience and reflection on what must be in place for them to have the sense they do.'
    ],['philosophy-of-mind','epistemology','continental-philosophy'],['husserl','heidegger','sartre','beauvoir','merleau-ponty','levinas'],['Ideas I','Being and Time','Phenomenology of Perception']),
    section('development','Husserl and the transformations of his project',[
      'Husserl emerged from work on mathematics, logic, and psychology. The Logical Investigations criticized the reduction of logical validity to psychological events and developed analyses of intentionality. Ideas I introduced the epoché and transcendental reduction as ways of suspending ordinary commitments in order to examine how objectivity is constituted. Later writings emphasize time-consciousness, embodiment, intersubjectivity, history, and the lifeworld. There is no single frozen “Husserlian method”; his project changed as difficulties about realism, transcendental subjectivity, and shared world became explicit.',
      'Heidegger’s Being and Time begins from the being for whom being is a question. Dasein is not a Cartesian mind placed inside a body but an engaged existence already involved with tools, projects, others, language, and mortality. Sartre reworks intentionality and nothingness into an account of consciousness and freedom. Beauvoir describes embodied and social situations in which freedom is unequally enabled. Merleau-Ponty argues that the lived body is not merely an object possessed by a mind but the practical orientation through which a world is available.',
      'Levinas learned from Husserl and Heidegger while criticizing philosophy’s tendency to make the other intelligible on the self’s terms. His account of the face and responsibility redirects phenomenological description toward ethics. Hermeneutic phenomenology emphasizes interpretation and historical tradition; later applied work studies experiences of illness, racialization, gender, disability, digital mediation, place, and ecological loss. These developments are not examples of one neutral technique applied to new topics. They revise what description, embodiment, world, and responsibility mean.'
    ],['existentialism','ethics','continental-philosophy'],['husserl','heidegger','sartre','beauvoir','merleau-ponty','levinas','gadamer'],['Logical Investigations','Being and Time','Totality and Infinity']),
    section('concepts','Intentionality, reduction, lifeworld, and embodiment',[
      'Intentionality means that consciousness is consciousness of something. It does not mean having a plan, and it does not imply that every object exists exactly as intended. A hallucinated object, remembered event, perceived chair, and imagined number are given in different modes. Phenomenology analyzes these differences and the horizons of expectation surrounding them. A perceived object shows one side while other sides are anticipated; its identity is available through a structured sequence of possible appearances rather than a view from nowhere.',
      'The epoché brackets or suspends the ordinary “natural attitude” in which the world’s existence is simply taken for granted. This is not denial that the world exists. It redirects attention toward how claims, objects, and evidence acquire meaning. Husserl’s transcendental reduction is controversial because it appears to relocate inquiry to constituting subjectivity. Realist and idealist interpretations dispute whether this clarifies objectivity or threatens to make the world dependent on consciousness. The disagreement belongs inside phenomenology rather than being settled by the word “description.”',
      'The lifeworld is the meaningful world of everyday practice presupposed by scientific abstraction. Embodiment shows that access to this world occurs through capacities, habits, vulnerability, and orientation. Merleau-Ponty’s body schema explains how one can reach, walk, or use a tool without first calculating coordinates. Heidegger’s readiness-to-hand similarly shows that equipment is first encountered through use. These accounts do not oppose science; they ask what forms of lived intelligibility scientific measurement abstracts from and still relies upon.'
    ],['philosophy-of-mind','epistemology','philosophy-of-science'],['husserl','heidegger','merleau-ponty'],['Ideas I','Phenomenology of Perception']),
    section('figures-works','Six trajectories through phenomenology',[
      'Husserl’s Logical Investigations offers early analyses of meaning and intentionality, Ideas I presents transcendental phenomenology, and The Crisis of European Sciences connects the lifeworld to the historical meaning of reason. Heidegger’s Being and Time transforms the field through care, worldhood, temporality, and being-toward-death. His project is ontological rather than a continuation of Husserl by minor adjustment, and his later work changes vocabulary and emphasis. His Nazi involvement must remain part of responsible historical study.',
      'Sartre’s Being and Nothingness analyzes consciousness, negation, freedom, bad faith, and the gaze. Beauvoir’s Ethics of Ambiguity and The Second Sex show that embodiment, social myth, labor, sexuality, and institutions shape a field of freedom. Her work is not merely Sartrean theory illustrated with women’s experience; it revises the philosophical account of situation and reciprocity. Merleau-Ponty’s Phenomenology of Perception makes bodily skill, ambiguity, and perceptual faith central, resisting both intellectualism and reductive empiricism.',
      'Levinas’s Totality and Infinity and Otherwise than Being argue that encounter with another person cannot be exhausted by representation or ontology. He is best treated as a critical heir whose ethical philosophy uses and unsettles phenomenology, not as though he simply belongs to the same program as Husserl. Later work should be named by its problem and method rather than grouped indiscriminately: hermeneutic, feminist, critical race, medical, disability, technological, and environmental phenomenologies develop different revisions and standards of evidence.'
    ],['existentialism','feminist-philosophy','ethics'],['husserl','heidegger','sartre','beauvoir','merleau-ponty','levinas'],['The Crisis of European Sciences','Being and Nothingness','The Second Sex','Totality and Infinity']),
    section('debates','Method, realism, alterity, and politics',[
      'Phenomenologists dispute whether reduction yields transcendental idealism, a refined realism, or a method that precedes this opposition. Husserl’s language of constitution can sound as if consciousness manufactures objects, although constitution concerns the disclosure and validation of their sense. Heidegger rejects the picture of a subject first enclosed within itself and then trying to reach a world. Merleau-Ponty emphasizes their intertwining. These differences determine whether phenomenology begins from consciousness, existence, body, or a more relational field.',
      'Intersubjectivity creates another dispute. How is another person given as another center of experience rather than as an observed body or projection? Husserl analyzes empathy and shared world; Sartre emphasizes the unsettling gaze; Beauvoir studies reciprocity and social othering; Levinas argues that the other exceeds phenomenological containment. Each response changes the ethical consequences of description. A method that describes how another appears can reproduce domination if it assumes the describer’s horizon is universal.',
      'The politics of phenomenology includes both resources and failures. Heidegger’s political commitment to Nazism cannot be treated as irrelevant biography, yet neither can it be resolved by a one-line verdict about every concept. Beauvoir, Fanon, and later critical phenomenologists expose gendered, racialized, colonial, and disabling structures within lived experience. Debate continues over whether first-person description can identify structural power, how testimony should function, and how researchers can avoid treating one experience as representative of a group.'
    ],['ethics','feminist-philosophy','political-philosophy'],['husserl','heidegger','sartre','beauvoir','levinas','fanon'],['The Second Sex','Totality and Infinity']),
    section('neighbors','Relations to existentialism, science, and hermeneutics',[
      'Existentialism inherits phenomenological methods but emphasizes the practical stakes of freedom, anxiety, mortality, and choice. Heidegger is crucial to that inheritance without fitting neatly under Sartrean existentialism. Sartre and Beauvoir are both phenomenologists and existential thinkers, while Merleau-Ponty’s work crosses those borders without being reducible to a movement label. Phenomenology is therefore the broader methodological genealogy; existentialism is one major transformation of it.',
      'Philosophy of mind and cognitive science engage phenomenology around perception, bodily skill, emotion, time-consciousness, and social cognition. Productive dialogue requires care: a phenomenological description is not automatically an experimental result, and a neurological explanation does not by itself replace the question of how an experience is lived. Approaches sometimes called embodied or enactive cognition share themes with phenomenology while operating with different methods and evidential standards.',
      'Hermeneutics argues that description is always shaped by language, history, and interpretation. Gadamer develops understanding through tradition and dialogue rather than a presuppositionless method. Ethics challenges any priority given to neutral disclosure, especially in Levinas. Feminist and critical phenomenologies show how bodily orientation and social space are structured by norms. These neighbors make phenomenology less a protected doctrine than a site where first-person, interpretive, social, and scientific accounts negotiate their limits.'
    ],['existentialism','philosophy-of-mind','philosophy-of-science','feminist-philosophy'],['heidegger','sartre','beauvoir','merleau-ponty','levinas','gadamer'],['Truth and Method']),
    section('misconceptions','More disciplined than reporting feelings',[
      'Phenomenology is not a diary of private feelings. A phenomenologist may begin from first-person experience, but the goal is to identify structures, variations, horizons, and conditions that make a kind of experience possible. Claims remain contestable and require careful description, comparison, and attention to difference. Saying “this is my lived experience” can be important testimony, but it does not by itself complete a phenomenological analysis or establish that everyone shares the same structure.',
      'Phenomenology also does not require rejecting natural science. Husserl’s critique of scientific objectivism concerns forgetting the lifeworld and the meaning of abstraction, not abandoning mathematics or experiment. Merleau-Ponty draws on psychology and neurology while resisting reductions that erase lived embodiment. A scientific causal account and a phenomenological account may answer different questions. Conflict arises when either claims to exhaust the phenomenon without explaining the other level.',
      'Finally, there is no single procedure unchanged from Husserl to contemporary applied work. Heidegger transforms the starting point, Sartre and Beauvoir connect it to freedom and social relations, Merleau-Ponty centers embodiment, and Levinas contests its grasp of alterity. Later uses should not add “phenomenology” to any interview study merely because it concerns experience. They should state what kind of reduction, interpretation, description, or critical method is being used and what warrants the conclusions.'
    ],['philosophy-of-science','epistemology'],['husserl','merleau-ponty','levinas'],['The Crisis of European Sciences']),
    section('modern-relevance','Experience under medicine, technology, and power',[
      'Medical phenomenology studies how illness changes bodily possibility, time, space, dependence, and relations with clinicians. A staircase can cease to be a neutral object and become an obstacle; waiting can transform the temporal shape of a day; a diagnosis can reorganize identity. These descriptions can improve clinical understanding without replacing biological explanation. Disability phenomenology likewise challenges assumptions that one bodily orientation defines normal access to a world.',
      'Digital technologies shape attention, memory, presence, and social encounter. Interface elements solicit action; notifications restructure temporal expectation; remote communication changes how bodies and others are present. Phenomenology can make these transformations visible before judging them, while political philosophy asks who designs and controls the systems. The method is especially useful for noticing what becomes habitual and therefore disappears from explicit attention.',
      'Critical phenomenologies analyze how racialization, gender, colonial history, and public space become lived orientations rather than merely external facts. They can show why formally identical environments offer unequal possibilities to different bodies. Environmental phenomenology studies attachment to place, ecological grief, and the perceptual consequences of treating nature only as resource. Across these uses, the discipline is to connect first-person meaning to shared structures without erasing variation or inflating a local description into a universal law.'
    ],['feminist-philosophy','political-philosophy','ethics'],['beauvoir','fanon','merleau-ponty'],['The Second Sex']),
    section('reading-path','Learning to see the method change',[
      'Begin with a short introduction to intentionality and read selected chapters from Husserl’s Idea of Phenomenology or Logical Investigations before attempting Ideas I. Practice by distinguishing perception, memory, imagination, and expectation in one ordinary example. Then read early sections of Heidegger’s Being and Time on being-in-the-world and equipment. The goal is not to memorize vocabulary but to see why engaged practical involvement challenges the model of a detached spectator.',
      'Continue with Merleau-Ponty on the lived body and Sartre on bad faith or the gaze. Read Beauvoir’s Ethics of Ambiguity and the introduction to The Second Sex to understand how social situation changes the meaning of freedom. Approach Levinas with guidance and treat him as a critic of phenomenological totalization. At every stage ask what is being described, what method authorizes the description, and how the thinker differs from Husserl rather than merely adding a new topic.',
      'Advanced reading can return to Husserl’s Crisis, study time-consciousness and intersubjectivity, follow Heidegger beyond Being and Time, and compare Merleau-Ponty’s later ontology with his earlier perception. Pair canonical texts with critical phenomenology and method debates in medicine, race, gender, and disability. A mature reading path should make it impossible to use “lived experience” as an unexplained trump card: phenomenological claims become stronger through methodological clarity, historical awareness, and openness to descriptions that unsettle one’s own horizon.'
    ],['philosophy-of-mind','existentialism','ethics'],['husserl','heidegger','sartre','beauvoir','merleau-ponty','levinas'],['The Idea of Phenomenology','Being and Time','Phenomenology of Perception'])
  ],
  'political-philosophy':[
    section('overview','The justification and organization of shared power',[
      'Political philosophy asks how people should live together under conditions of disagreement, dependence, scarcity, and power. Its questions include who may rule, what makes authority legitimate, which liberties and rights people have, how benefits and burdens should be distributed, and what citizens owe one another. It also asks how family, property, labor, race, gender, empire, religion, and economic institutions shape political standing. The field is normative and historical: it evaluates arrangements while examining the concepts and conflicts through which arrangements became thinkable.',
      'Politics here does not mean election strategy, party identity, or commentary on the latest controversy. Those practices raise philosophical questions, but the field asks about standards that can assess parties and policies. Nor is political philosophy only social-contract theory. Contract arguments form one influential early modern family; ancient virtue and citizenship, republican freedom, utilitarian reform, Marxist critique, feminist theory, anticolonial thought, capabilities, deliberative democracy, and non-Western traditions offer different starting points.',
      'The central difficulty is that collective power can be necessary and dangerous at once. Laws can coordinate action, secure rights, and provide public goods, yet coercion can entrench domination. Markets can enable exchange while concentrating control. Democratic decisions can express equal standing while excluding minorities or future generations. Political philosophy therefore asks not simply what ideal institutions look like, but who has voice, how power operates beyond formal law, and what agents should do when actual institutions are unjust.'
    ],['ethics','feminist-philosophy'],['plato','aristotle','hobbes','rousseau','rawls','arendt'],['Republic','Politics','A Theory of Justice']),
    section('development','Many histories of political argument',[
      'Plato’s Republic connects justice in the city to education, expertise, desire, and the soul; Aristotle’s Politics compares constitutions and treats political association as part of human flourishing. Chinese traditions offer different debates: Confucian cultivation and exemplary rule, Mohist impartial benefit, and Legalist institutions, law, technique, and power. Al-Farabi’s virtuous city joins philosophy, prophecy, and political order. Medieval Christian, Jewish, and Islamic thinkers debate law, authority, civic peace, and the relation between religious and temporal power.',
      'Machiavelli analyzes founding, conflict, necessity, and the preservation of political orders without assuming conventional moral vocabulary is sufficient. Hobbes, Locke, and Rousseau use states of nature and social agreements to explain legitimacy in sharply different ways. Montesquieu studies how institutions and social conditions shape law. Wollstonecraft exposes the contradiction between universal liberty and women’s subordination. Mill connects liberty and utility; Marx analyzes class, labor, property, and ideology rather than treating legal equality as the whole of freedom.',
      'Twentieth-century political philosophy includes Arendt on action, totalitarianism, and public worlds; Rawls on justice as fairness; Nozick’s libertarian challenge; feminist critiques of the public/private division; Habermas on communication and democracy; and anticolonial and decolonial work on empire and racial power. Fanon analyzes colonial violence and subject formation. Capabilities, global justice, disability justice, abolition, and climate ethics extend the field. There is no single timeline in which European contract theory naturally becomes the universal framework.'
    ],['chinese-philosophy','islamic-philosophy','feminist-philosophy','continental-philosophy'],['plato','aristotle','al-farabi','machiavelli','hobbes','locke','rousseau','wollstonecraft','mill','marx','arendt','rawls','nozick','fanon'],['Leviathan','The Social Contract','On Liberty']),
    section('concepts','Legitimacy, liberty, equality, justice, and power',[
      'Legitimacy asks when an institution has the right to issue and enforce rules, not merely whether it can compel obedience. Consent, public justification, democratic authorization, beneficial outcomes, tradition, and protection of rights are rival or complementary answers. Political obligation asks whether citizens normally have a duty to obey and what defeats that duty. Civil disobedience, resistance, revolution, and conscientious refusal test the gap between legality and legitimacy.',
      'Liberty can mean noninterference, protection from arbitrary domination, or effective capacity to act. Equality can concern legal status, political voice, resources, opportunity, capabilities, or social relations. These concepts do not mechanically oppose each other. Property rights may protect independence while unequal property can undermine effective freedom and political equality. Justice names standards for institutions, recognition, punishment, repair, distribution, and historical wrong; no one formula resolves every domain.',
      'Power includes more than commands issued by a state. Employers, families, property regimes, racial hierarchies, gender norms, colonial borders, prisons, and platforms can structure options and identities. Arendt distinguishes power arising through collective action from violence; Marxist and critical traditions examine class and ideology; feminist theory shows how allegedly private relations are political. A theory focused only on formal law may miss domination, while a theory treating power as everywhere must still distinguish kinds, agents, and possible remedies.'
    ],['ethics','feminist-philosophy','continental-philosophy'],['arendt','marx','foucault','rawls'],['The Human Condition','Discipline and Punish']),
    section('figures-works','Canonical arguments and challenges to the canon',[
      'Plato’s Republic asks whether justice benefits the just person and constructs a provocative educational and political order. Aristotle’s Politics studies constitutions and citizenship while excluding women, enslaved people, and laborers from equal standing. Hobbes’s Leviathan grounds authority in the need to escape insecurity; Locke’s Second Treatise links limited government to rights and property; Rousseau’s Social Contract seeks freedom through collective self-rule. Their “states of nature” are philosophical constructions, not neutral reports of prehistoric society.',
      'Machiavelli’s Prince and Discourses examine power and republican conflict. Wollstonecraft’s Vindication of the Rights of Woman exposes how denied education manufactures the inequality invoked to justify exclusion. Mill’s On Liberty defends individuality and limits on social coercion. Marx’s writings analyze exploitation and historical forms of production. These works expand politics beyond constitutional design into social formation, economy, and the unequal capacity to develop and exercise agency.',
      'Rawls’s A Theory of Justice models fair choice through an original position behind a veil of ignorance; Nozick’s Anarchy, State, and Utopia defends historical entitlement and a minimal state. Arendt’s Human Condition distinguishes labor, work, and action. Fanon’s Wretched of the Earth addresses colonial domination and liberation. Beauvoir, Habermas, Nussbaum, Davis, and hooks open different questions about gender, communication, capabilities, abolition, race, and class. Rawls versus Nozick is one debate, not the definition of contemporary political philosophy.'
    ],['feminist-philosophy','utilitarianism','ethics'],['plato','aristotle','machiavelli','hobbes','locke','rousseau','wollstonecraft','mill','marx','rawls','nozick','arendt','fanon','beauvoir','habermas','martha-nussbaum','angela-davis','bell-hooks'],['The Prince','A Vindication of the Rights of Woman','Anarchy, State, and Utopia']),
    section('debates','Authority, distribution, democracy, and nonideal justice',[
      'Social-contract theories disagree about both the problem and the agreement. Hobbes emphasizes security under a sovereign; Locke protects natural rights and allows resistance; Rousseau seeks a general will through which citizens obey laws they prescribe collectively. The general will is not simply whatever a majority happens to want. Critics ask whether hypothetical consent can justify real coercion and whether contract traditions conceal conquest, patriarchy, enslavement, and colonial dispossession behind a picture of free and equal contractors.',
      'Distributive debates compare welfare, resources, primary goods, capabilities, desert, need, equality, and entitlement. Rawls permits inequalities only under demanding conditions of fair opportunity and benefit to the least advantaged; Nozick rejects patterned redistribution when holdings arise justly. Capability approaches ask what people can actually do and be. Historical injustice complicates any snapshot: current distributions can reflect theft, exclusion, unpaid care, and racialized accumulation that an abstract pattern fails to register.',
      'Democratic theory disputes voting, deliberation, representation, contestation, expertise, and participation. Nonideal theory asks how to reason amid injustice rather than only describe a perfectly just society. Civil disobedience and abolition test whether reform presupposes too much legitimacy in existing institutions. Global and climate justice challenge borders around obligation, while future generations cannot consent or vote. Political philosophy must connect principles to institutions without pretending either that a blueprint guarantees compliance or that realism requires surrendering standards.'
    ],['ethics','feminist-philosophy'],['hobbes','locke','rousseau','rawls','nozick','martha-nussbaum','angela-davis'],['Leviathan','The Social Contract','A Theory of Justice']),
    section('neighbors','Ethics, economics, law, and social critique',[
      'Political philosophy overlaps ethics because institutions distribute opportunities to live well and make action possible or costly. Yet it cannot simply scale individual morality upward. States claim coercive authority, collective decisions involve persistent disagreement, and institutional rules produce patterns no person intended. Virtue ethics asks what citizens and leaders should become; deontology emphasizes rights and duties; utilitarianism compares social consequences. Political theories borrow from each while facing distinctive questions of legitimacy and implementation.',
      'Law gives political principles institutional form but legality does not settle justice. Economics models incentives, production, exchange, and distribution, while political philosophy asks what goals and rights those models should serve and whose costs count. Marx and later critical traditions contest the idea that economic arrangements form a neutral private sphere. Feminist philosophy likewise shows that family, care, reproduction, and violence cannot be excluded as merely personal without preserving political hierarchy.',
      'History and social science inform which institutions exist and how they work; normative argument clarifies why evidence matters and what should change. Chinese, Islamic, Indian, African, Indigenous, and other traditions challenge the assumption that European categories exhaust political thought. Within this atlas, links to Confucianism, Mohism, Legalism, Islamic philosophy, feminist philosophy, ethics, and continental critique should signal genuine alternative problems and genealogies, not decorate an otherwise unchanged Western survey.'
    ],['ethics','deontology','utilitarianism','feminist-philosophy','chinese-philosophy','islamic-philosophy'],['aristotle','kant','bentham','mill','marx','beauvoir'],['Nicomachean Ethics','Groundwork of the Metaphysics of Morals']),
    section('misconceptions','What political philosophy is not',[
      'Political philosophy is not party politics with footnotes. A theory of liberty, equality, or legitimacy may criticize several parties or expose assumptions shared across a political spectrum. Contemporary examples can make concepts concrete, but attaching a doctrine to a current coalition too quickly makes the material date badly and hides internal disagreement. The relevant question is what reasons support an institution or policy, how concepts are defined, and who bears its risks and benefits.',
      'The field is not exhausted by Hobbes, Locke, Rousseau, Rawls, and Nozick. Social contract and distributive justice are central, but republicanism, Marxism, anarchism, feminism, anticolonial thought, capabilities, critical race theory, Confucian political ethics, Islamic political philosophy, and theories of democracy pose different questions. Nor should “Western political philosophy” be presented as though it developed without empire, translation, religious traditions, or encounters with other societies.',
      'Political thinkers also should not be reduced to slogans. Hobbes does not merely say people are selfish; Rousseau’s general will is not majority preference; Mill’s harm principle does not answer every case by itself; Marx does not reduce all events to a simple economic cause; Rawls’s veil of ignorance is a device of representation, not proposed amnesia in actual voting. Accurate beginner explanation preserves the problem each device was designed to address and the objections it attracts.'
    ],['ethics','chinese-philosophy','islamic-philosophy'],['hobbes','rousseau','mill','marx','rawls'],['On Liberty','A Theory of Justice']),
    section('modern-relevance','Institutions that govern contemporary life',[
      'Digital platforms exercise rule-like power over speech, visibility, work, and association. Political philosophy asks whether such power requires democratic accountability, due process, transparency, or rights analogous to those limiting governments. Automated decisions raise questions of equal treatment, explanation, and responsibility. Describing a system as privately owned does not settle whether its effects are politically significant, just as calling regulation public does not guarantee legitimacy.',
      'Climate change joins distribution, history, borders, and future generations. Who should pay depends on capacity, benefit, contribution, vulnerability, and colonial history. Migration tests whether citizenship can morally determine access to safety and opportunity. Public health tests liberty, trust, expertise, and collective risk. None of these problems is solved by choosing liberty over equality in the abstract; each requires specifying kinds of freedom, institutional alternatives, evidence, and the distribution of uncertainty.',
      'Movements concerning racial justice, gender equality, disability, Indigenous sovereignty, and abolition expose the limits of formally equal rights when institutions remain structured by inherited domination. Political philosophy can clarify competing proposals, but it must also learn from testimony, history, and organizing rather than treating affected people as examples for theories made elsewhere. Its modern relevance lies in connecting ideals to the design, repair, or replacement of institutions through which people share a world.'
    ],['feminist-philosophy','philosophy-of-science','ethics'],['arendt','fanon','martha-nussbaum','angela-davis','bell-hooks'],['The Human Condition']),
    section('reading-path','Build a comparative map of political questions',[
      'Begin with short selections that pose different central problems: Plato on justice, Aristotle on citizenship, Confucius or the Mohists on ethical rule and public benefit, and al-Farabi on the virtuous city. Then compare Machiavelli’s institutional realism with Hobbes, Locke, and Rousseau on authority. Treat each state of nature and contract as an argumentative model. Ask what problem political order solves, who counts as a party, and when resistance is justified.',
      'Add Wollstonecraft and Mill before moving to Marx, because liberty, education, gender, class, and economy should develop together. Read Arendt on action and public life, then Rawls and Nozick as a focused dispute rather than a complete map. Pair them with Beauvoir, Fanon, capabilities work, and abolitionist or critical race arguments. Keep a comparison table for authority, liberty, equality, property, democracy, inclusion, and change.',
      'Advanced reading should combine ideal and nonideal theory, global justice, democratic theory, feminism, colonial history, and institutional analysis. Read primary texts alongside histories explaining who was excluded from their political world. For every proposal ask what agents could implement it, how power might evade it, what transition it requires, and how failure would be corrected. Political philosophy becomes useful when principles remain demanding while engaging actual histories and mechanisms.'
    ],['ethics','feminist-philosophy','chinese-philosophy','islamic-philosophy'],['plato','aristotle','al-farabi','machiavelli','hobbes','locke','rousseau','wollstonecraft','mill','marx','arendt','rawls','nozick','fanon'],['Republic','The Prince','Leviathan','A Vindication of the Rights of Woman'])
  ],
  'philosophy-of-science':[
    section('overview','How scientific inquiry earns and revises authority',[
      'Philosophy of science asks what makes scientific inquiry reliable, explanatory, and distinct without assuming that all sciences use one timeless method. It studies observation, experiment, measurement, models, laws, causation, probability, confirmation, explanation, and theory change. It also examines the institutions through which evidence is produced: instruments, laboratories, peer criticism, standards, funding, and communities of specialists. The field does not confer a simple badge called “scientific”; it investigates how particular claims become warranted and remain open to correction.',
      'The central problem joins success to fallibility. Scientific theories predict and explain phenomena with extraordinary power, yet observations are selective, instruments require interpretation, and past theories have been replaced. How can evidence support claims extending beyond observed cases? What distinguishes productive revision from protecting a theory at any cost? Why do some explanations reveal causes while others merely fit data? Bacon, Hume, Popper, Kuhn, logical empiricists, pragmatists, and contemporary philosophers give importantly different answers.',
      'Philosophy of science is not an instruction manual written by outsiders telling scientists how to perform every experiment. Historical and current scientific practice supplies its evidence, while philosophical analysis clarifies concepts and standards often left implicit. The relation is critical in both directions: philosophy can expose invalid inferences or confused demarcation claims, and scientific practice can overturn philosophical pictures built around an imaginary method. Good work moves between cases and general arguments.'
    ],['epistemology','logic','empiricism'],['bacon','hume','popper','kuhn','carnap'],['Novum Organum','The Logic of Scientific Discovery','The Structure of Scientific Revolutions']),
    section('development','From experimental reform to historical models',[
      'Francis Bacon’s Novum Organum attacks inherited idols of thought and advocates organized inquiry, comparison, and experiment. He did not single-handedly invent modern science, nor did he propose that facts speak without hypotheses. His program belongs within a larger transformation involving mathematical physics, instruments, craft knowledge, institutions, and global extraction. Hume later formulates the problem of induction: past regularities cannot noncircularly prove that unobserved cases will resemble observed ones. His analysis of causation makes habit and inference central to empirical knowledge.',
      'Nineteenth- and early twentieth-century debates examined induction, laws, measurement, and explanation. Logical empiricists such as Carnap used logic and probability to clarify scientific language and confirmation while rejecting much traditional metaphysics. Their projects were diverse and changed over time; “positivism” should not function as a dismissive label for one crude verification doctrine. Popper shifted emphasis from verification to risky testing and falsifiability, arguing that bold conjectures advance through criticism rather than accumulation of confirming instances.',
      'Kuhn’s Structure of Scientific Revolutions brought history of science to the center. Normal science works within paradigms that organize exemplary problems, standards, and techniques; anomalies can contribute to crises and revolutionary change. Later work by many philosophers analyzes research programs, experimental practice, models, mechanisms, realism, values, social organization, and individual sciences. The development is not a sequence in which each new theory of science simply falsifies the previous one. Competing accounts illuminate different scales and episodes of inquiry.'
    ],['empiricism','analytic-philosophy','pragmatism'],['bacon','hume','carnap','popper','kuhn'],['An Enquiry Concerning Human Understanding','The Logical Structure of the World']),
    section('concepts','Evidence, confirmation, explanation, and theory',[
      'Evidence does not support a claim merely by occurring nearby. Experiments require controls, measurements require models of instruments, and statistical results depend on assumptions about sampling and alternatives. Confirmation theories ask how observations change rational confidence. Hume’s problem of induction explains why no finite set of positive instances deductively entails a universal law. Responses include probabilistic, Bayesian, reliabilist, pragmatic, and rule-based accounts; none licenses the slogan that science simply proves theories from facts.',
      'Explanation may cite causes, laws, mechanisms, unifying patterns, models, or counterfactual dependence. A prediction can be accurate without explaining, and an explanation can concern an event already known. Different sciences legitimately emphasize different forms: particle physics, evolutionary biology, geology, epidemiology, and social science do not always seek the same kind of answer. Philosophers ask when an idealized model explains despite being literally false and how causal claims can be distinguished from correlation.',
      'Theories organize concepts, equations, models, and practices rather than forming isolated sentences tested one at a time. Observations can be theory-laden because background concepts and instruments shape what counts as data, but this does not make observation arbitrary. Independent techniques, calibration, replication, intervention, and criticism can constrain interpretation. Underdetermination arises when evidence fits multiple accounts; it invites attention to explanatory virtues and future tests, not automatic skepticism about every scientific conclusion.'
    ],['epistemology','logic'],['hume','carnap'],['An Enquiry Concerning Human Understanding']),
    section('figures-works','Bacon, Hume, Popper, Kuhn, and their contexts',[
      'Bacon’s Novum Organum presents induction as a disciplined ascent using carefully organized comparisons and exclusions, joined to an analysis of cognitive and social error. His rhetoric of mastering nature and the imperial context of knowledge require critical attention. Hume’s Enquiry examines causal inference, testimony, probability, and miracles; he does not claim people should stop relying on induction. He shows that this reliance cannot be grounded by the deductive proof philosophers sometimes demand and instead belongs to human cognitive practice.',
      'Carnap’s work represents logical empiricism’s ambition to clarify scientific concepts through formal languages, probability, and frameworks. Popper’s Logic of Scientific Discovery argues that universal theories cannot be conclusively verified but can expose themselves to refutation. Falsifiability is primarily a proposal about empirical testability and demarcation, not a claim that scientists instantly discard a theory after any conflict. Popper also emphasizes corroboration, methodological decisions, and ongoing criticism.',
      'Kuhn’s Structure of Scientific Revolutions studies how paradigms guide puzzle-solving and how standards can change during revolutions. “Paradigm” has several related uses in the book, a source of later clarification. Kuhn does not say evidence is irrelevant, all paradigms are equally good, or science never progresses. He complicates the picture of progress as steady accumulation and asks how communities compare achievements when standards and vocabularies shift. Popper and Kuhn therefore highlight different modes—critical testing and historically organized practice—rather than offering two slogans that exhaust science.'
    ],['empiricism','analytic-philosophy'],['bacon','hume','carnap','popper','kuhn'],['Novum Organum','An Enquiry Concerning Human Understanding','The Logic of Scientific Discovery','The Structure of Scientific Revolutions']),
    section('debates','Demarcation, falsification, realism, and change',[
      'Demarcation asks how science differs from pseudoscience, metaphysics, or other inquiry. Popper’s falsifiability captures the importance of risky empirical consequences, but no single criterion cleanly classifies every mature science and excludes every imitation. Historical sciences, probabilistic hypotheses, complex models, and research programs may be testable in distributed ways. Pseudoscientific communities can also stage apparent tests while insulating central commitments. Demarcation often requires a cluster of practices: evidential accountability, methodological transparency, critical exchange, and responsiveness to failure.',
      'Simplistic falsification ignores that a prediction follows from a theory together with auxiliary assumptions about instruments, initial conditions, and background knowledge. A failed prediction does not logically identify which component is wrong. Scientists may reasonably check calibration or modify an auxiliary assumption, but endless ad hoc rescue can drain a theory of content. The philosophical task is to distinguish progressive adjustment from evasion. Popper’s own account is more sophisticated than the classroom rule “one counterexample kills a theory,” though critics still find its picture incomplete.',
      'Scientific realism holds, in varying forms, that successful mature theories warrant belief in unobservable entities or structures; antirealist positions emphasize empirical adequacy, models, or caution based on past replacement. Kuhnian theory change raises questions about incommensurability: if concepts and standards change, how are paradigms compared? Incommensurability is not total incomparability. Translation can be difficult and losses real while evidence, problem-solving, precision, and new phenomena still matter. Values enter choices without making them merely political preference.'
    ],['epistemology','skepticism'],['popper','kuhn','quine'],['The Logic of Scientific Discovery','The Structure of Scientific Revolutions']),
    section('neighbors','Empiricism, pragmatism, logic, and social inquiry',[
      'Empiricism supplies philosophy of science with attention to observation and evidential limits. Baconian experiment, Humean induction, and later logical empiricism are not one doctrine, and reason is never absent from their accounts. Logic clarifies entailment, probability, and models, but formal validity alone cannot determine which measurements are trustworthy or which explanations matter. Epistemology broadens the discussion to testimony and expertise, crucial because no individual can personally reproduce most evidence they reasonably accept.',
      'Pragmatism treats inquiry as an error-correcting practice oriented toward consequences and communal investigation. Peirce’s fallibilism and Dewey’s account of inquiry offer alternatives to both certainty and radical skepticism. Sociology and history of science reveal laboratories, institutions, incentives, and power. Philosophers debate how to incorporate these findings without reducing evidence to social negotiation. Scientific knowledge is socially produced and can still be constrained by a world that resists expectations.',
      'Ethics and political philosophy enter research through risk, consent, public funding, environmental harm, data governance, and the distribution of benefits. Feminist philosophy of science has shown how background assumptions and exclusion can shape questions while also developing stronger practices of objectivity and criticism. Connections to analytic philosophy, empiricism, pragmatism, epistemology, and politics should display philosophy of science as an intersection, not as a narrow contest between Popper and Kuhn.'
    ],['empiricism','pragmatism','logic','epistemology','political-philosophy','feminist-philosophy'],['bacon','hume','peirce','dewey','popper','kuhn'],['How to Make Our Ideas Clear']),
    section('misconceptions','No single mechanical scientific method',[
      'Science does not proceed through one universal sequence of observe, hypothesize, experiment, and prove. Astronomy, field biology, paleontology, mathematics-intensive physics, clinical trials, and social science use different combinations of observation, intervention, simulation, comparison, and modeling. Shared norms can exist without one algorithm. Bacon did not merely command investigators to collect facts, and empiricism does not exclude concepts, mathematics, or creative hypothesis.',
      'Falsifiability is not a magic stamp of truth. A false claim can be testable, and a valuable research program can face anomalies without immediate abandonment. Popper’s proposal emphasizes vulnerability to criticism; actual appraisal considers auxiliaries, severity of tests, alternative explanations, replication, and a program’s ability to generate knowledge. Conversely, endlessly adjusting a claim after every outcome can reveal that no genuine risk was taken. The judgment is methodological and historical, not a one-line logical test.',
      'Kuhn did not prove that science is irrational or that facts are whatever a community votes them to be. Paradigms organize attention and standards, but nature can produce persistent anomalies, and revolutions can increase accuracy, scope, and problem-solving power. “Theory-laden” does not mean “made up,” and recognizing values does not mean all conclusions are partisan. These cautions allow serious discussion of bias and power without collapsing the difference between disciplined inquiry and propaganda.'
    ],['empiricism','skepticism'],['bacon','popper','kuhn'],['The Structure of Scientific Revolutions']),
    section('modern-relevance','Trust, models, crises, and public evidence',[
      'Public controversies about climate, pandemics, nutrition, and environmental risk require reasoning from models, uncertain data, and expert testimony. Philosophy of science clarifies why uncertainty does not imply ignorance and why changing recommendations can reflect learning rather than fraud. It also explains why consensus is evidentially significant without becoming infallible: relevant communities combine specialized evidence, criticism, and independent methods, while remaining vulnerable to distorted incentives and exclusion.',
      'Machine learning intensifies questions about prediction and explanation. A model may classify accurately while obscuring causal structure or failing under changed conditions. Researchers must distinguish training performance, generalization, calibration, interpretability, and causal relevance. The older philosophical difference between saving appearances and understanding mechanisms becomes practically urgent when systems affect medicine, employment, or law. Statistical success alone does not settle whether deployment is safe or just.',
      'Replication debates, publication bias, and industry funding show that reliability depends on institutions as well as individual virtue. Open methods, preregistration, data access, adversarial testing, and diverse research communities can improve correction, though none is a universal cure. Philosophy of science contributes by identifying which failure a reform addresses and what tradeoffs it introduces. Its modern relevance is an account of warranted trust that avoids both blind deference and reflexive suspicion.'
    ],['political-philosophy','ethics','epistemology'],['popper','kuhn'],['The Logic of Scientific Discovery']),
    section('reading-path','From induction to contemporary practice',[
      'Begin with Bacon’s discussion of the idols and selected examples of his inductive method, then read Hume’s sections on causal inference and induction. Ask why repeated observations cannot deductively guarantee the next case and why inquiry nevertheless remains possible. A beginner overview of confirmation and explanation can then distinguish logical support, probability, causation, mechanism, and model before the famous twentieth-century debates are introduced.',
      'Read accessible selections from Popper on conjecture, testability, and corroboration, followed by Kuhn’s Structure of Scientific Revolutions. For Popper, record the role of auxiliaries and methodological decisions; for Kuhn, distinguish normal science, anomaly, crisis, revolution, and incommensurability. Add Carnap or a history of logical empiricism so that the movement is not reduced to a foil. Compare each account against one scientific episode rather than arguing only through abstract slogans.',
      'Advanced study should include scientific realism, Bayesian confirmation, causal explanation, models and idealization, values in science, feminist philosophy of science, and social epistemology. Choose case studies from more than physics: evolutionary biology, medicine, climate science, or social research reveal different methods. The final test is practical: explain why a piece of evidence supports a claim, what alternatives remain, what institutional checks matter, and what future result should rationally change confidence.'
    ],['empiricism','epistemology','pragmatism'],['bacon','hume','carnap','popper','kuhn'],['Novum Organum','An Enquiry Concerning Human Understanding','The Structure of Scientific Revolutions'])
  ]
};

